#[doc("""
stdlib/net/udp.kai — surface helpers on top of the NetUdp effect.
Spec: docs/effects-stdlib.md §`NetUdp`. The effect itself is
declared by the compiler (stage2 builtin_netudp_decl); this file
adds the small pure / forwarding helpers that fall out of the v1
op set, mirroring stdlib/net/tcp.kai.

Module path: `import net.udp`. The catalog and naming convention
live in docs/stdlib-layout.md §`net`.

v1 limitations are pinned in stdlib/effects.kai's NetUdp note:
IPv4 only, blocking ops, [Byte] lands as [Int], SocketAddr.host is
a textual dotted-quad, Result type-arg order flipped to kaikai's
Err-first convention, no `Net` alias yet (waits on net.dns / #352).

No `with_udp` installer ships in v1: the NetUdp default handler is
auto-installed around `main` by the runtime when `/ NetUdp` is in
the row (same as NetTcp — there is no `with_tcp` either). A
kaikai-bodied `with_udp` that re-installs the handler would need
`$extern_handler` inside a `handle ... with NetUdp { ... }` block,
which the codegen rejects outside an effect `default { }` block
(Stage C of #533). Listed as a follow-up in the lane retro.
""")]

#[doc("""
Read back the local port a UdpSocket is bound to. Useful when the
caller passed `port = 0` to `bind`, asking the kernel to pick a
free port — the assigned value lands in the UdpSocket record's
`port` slot at bind time (see kai_default_netudp_bind in
stage0/runtime.h).
""")]
pub fn local_port(s: UdpSocket) : Int = s.port

#[doc("""
Bind a UDP socket to `host:port`. `host = ""` or `"0.0.0.0"` binds
INADDR_ANY; `port = 0` asks the kernel for an ephemeral port,
readable afterwards via `local_port`. Err-first Result.
""")]
pub fn bind(host: String, port: Int) : Result[String, UdpSocket] / NetUdp =
  NetUdp.bind(host, port)

#[doc("""
Send a datagram of `data` (a [Int], each element truncated to a
byte) to `dst`. Returns the byte count sent on success.
""")]
pub fn send(s: UdpSocket, dst: SocketAddr, data: [Int]) : Result[String, Int] / NetUdp =
  NetUdp.send(s, dst, data)

#[doc("""
Receive one datagram of at most `max` bytes. Returns the source
address paired with the received bytes (kaikai has no tuples, so
the pair is a `Pair[SocketAddr, [Int]]` record with `fst` / `snd`
slots). `max <= 0` is a panic — there is no useful "read zero
bytes" call.
""")]
pub fn recv(s: UdpSocket, max: Int) : Result[String, Pair[SocketAddr, [Int]]] / NetUdp =
  NetUdp.recv(s, max)

#[doc("""
Close a UDP socket. Errors from close(2) are logged and swallowed
by the handler — there is nothing useful a caller can do with
them — so the surface op returns Unit.
""")]
pub fn close(s: UdpSocket) : Unit / NetUdp =
  NetUdp.close(s)

#[doc("""
Construct a SocketAddr from a textual IPv4 host and a port. Pure
helper so callers building a `send` destination do not need the
`SocketAddr { ... }` record literal at every call site.
""")]
pub fn addr(host: String, port: Int) : SocketAddr =
  SocketAddr { host: host, port: port }
